By the definition of a derivative, we have that

\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}\\
&= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\frac{x+h}{x + h + 5} - \frac{x}{x+5} }{h} \end{align*}

The key step to simplifying this expression is here: we find a common
denominator for the fractions on top and combine them.

\begin{align*}
&= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\frac{(x+h)(x+5)}{(x + h + 5)(x+5)} - \frac{x(x+h+5)}{(x+h+5)(x+5)} }{h} \\
&= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\frac{x^{2} + xh + 5x + 5h - x^{2} - xh - 5x}{(x + h + 5)(x+5) }}{h} \end{align*}

Now we simplify the expression into a single fraction and cancel the
\emph{h} on top and bottom.

\begin{align*}
&= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{5h}{h(x + h + 5)(x+5)} \\
&= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{5}{(x + h + 5)(x+5)} \end{align*}

Finally taking the limit gives:

\begin{align*}
&= \frac{5}{(x + 5)(x+5)} \\
&= \frac{5}{(x + 5)^{2}} 
\end{align*}

Using the alternative definition,

\begin{align*}
 f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x-a} \\
 f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{\frac{x}{x+5} - \frac{a}{a+5}}{x-a} \end{align*}

Here we find a common denominator to simplify the fractions on top of
the large fraction.

\begin{align*} f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{\frac{x(a+5)}{(x+5)(a+5)} - \frac{a(x+5)}{(a+5)(x+5)}}{x-a} \\
 f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{\frac{xa+5x - ax - 5a}{(x+5)(a+5)} }{x-a} \end{align*}

We then simplify the fraction, factoring out a 5 on top and then
canceling the \emph{(x - a)} term.

\begin{align*}
 f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{5x - 5a}{(x+5)(a+5)(x-a)} \\
 f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{5(x - a)}{(x+5)(a+5)(x-a)} \\
 f'(a) &= \lim_{x \to a} \frac{5}{(x+5)(a+5)} \end{align*}

Finally we take the limit.

\begin{align*}
 f'(a) &= \frac{5}{(a+5)(a+5)} \\
 f'(a) &= \frac{5}{(a+5)^{2}} \\
\end{align*}

Which completes the question.
